@flexiarg writing-coherence/section-bridge-missing
@title Bridge the Section Boundary

@keywords section-boundary, transition, connective-tissue, paragraph-break, finding-vs-positioning
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/throat-clearing-close, writing-coherence/meta-lede]

! conclusion: A section boundary is the place where the reader most needs help: the closing paragraph must name what has been established, and the next opening paragraph must name what is now to be addressed.  When the closing sentence reads as a finding rather than a positioning move, and the next section begins cold, the reader cannot tell whether the closing claim was the section's conclusion or its setup.  The section-to-section connective tissue has been silently elided, and the argument's spine goes invisible at exactly the joints.
  + context: AI drafts and condensed academic prose both tend to drop the bridge.  Each paragraph stands locally well, and each section opens with a competent topic sentence; but the relationship between them has been left to the reader to reconstruct from the section titles alone.  Reviewers experience this as "the argument jumps" even when no individual paragraph is weak.  Distinct from `throat-clearing-close` (which is about ending on attitude rather than claim) and from `meta-lede` (which is about opening on shape rather than content): here the diagnostic is the *transition*, not either sentence in isolation.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: local paragraph competence ↔ argumentative continuity across sections.
    Real: a strong closing paragraph orients the reader to what has just been established; a strong opening paragraph names what is now at stake.  Without both, the section boundary asserts a structural break the argument never repairs.
    Irreducible: the bridge cannot be supplied by section titles alone — titles signal topic, but the reader needs the argumentative move from one to the next.
    Active: the pull recurs at every section break, and is strongest where the writer has been deep inside one section and forgets that the reader is about to leave it.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Close on positioning: rewrite the closing sentence so it names what the section established AND points at what remains open.  "Frameworks for collective stewardship therefore direct attention away from individual motivation and toward whether the institutional conditions are in place."
    (2) Open on connection: add a connective sentence at the start of the next section that names the move being made.  "A complementary perspective comes from implementation science, which distinguishes adoption from implementation from sustainability."
    (3) Audit at every break: read the last sentence of section N immediately followed by the first sentence of section N+1, with nothing else.  If the move from one to the other is not legible from those two sentences, the bridge is missing.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the last sentence of each section reads as a positioning move AND the first sentence of the next section names what is now being addressed.  Failing when: either the close reads as a finding without forward orientation, or the open begins cold without acknowledging what the previous section established.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Cold open: the next section begins with a topic sentence that ignores the closing claim of the previous section.
    - Finding-as-close: the closing sentence asserts a result without orienting the reader to what is next.
    - Title-as-bridge: the writer relies on the section title to do the connective work, leaving the reader to infer the argumentative move.
